  "abstract": "We have established a phonotactic language model as the solution to spoken language identification (LID). In this framework, we define a single set of acoustic tokens to represent the acoustic activities in the worldâ€™s spoken languages. A voice tokenizer converts a spoken document into a text-like document of acoustic tokens. Thus a spoken document can be represented by a count vector of acoustic tokens and token n-grams in the vector space. We apply latent semantic analysis to the vectors, in the same way that it is applied in information retrieval, in order to capture salient phonotactics present in spoken documents. The vector space modeling of spoken utterances constitutes a paradigm shift in LID technology and has proven to be very successful. It presents a 12.4 % error rate reduction over one of the best reported results on",
